[1] Texas
Date: Tue 3 Sep 2013
Source: KENS 5, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.kens5.com/news/222217421.html


Texas health officials say the number of people sick with whooping cough [pertussis] statewide is on track to reach the highest level in more than 50 years. The Texas Department of State Health Services on Tuesday, 3 Sep 2013, urged people to make sure they are vaccinated against the highly contagious disease that causes a severe cough.

There have been almost 2000 cases reported so far in 2013 with the annual total likely to surpass the recent high of 3358 cases in 2009. In 2013, 2 infants have died from whooping cough; both were too young to be vaccinated.

The infection spreads easily through the air when an infected person breathes, coughs or sneezes. While infants are most at risk, people of all ages can get whooping cough.

